<font color="#FF0000">A REPLY TO ALL...</font><br>
<tt>Wed Aug 20  1:34:03 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Dear Friends,<br><br>
Sorry for this late response. Missed some medication Sunday and have really been sick.<br><br>
Well, what can I say? THANK YOU, THANK YOU, THANK YOU! I’m really sincere about that. I’ll tell you the truth, I’d thought about chucking it all a few hours ago but decided to check for any responses first. Christ, I was overwhelmed. ALL OF YOU REALLY MADE A DIFFERENCE. I cannot ever be thankful enough.<br><br>
It occurred to me for the first time yesterday that a lot of guys (long range artillery, etc.) never actually saw the results of their efforts (maybe it was just as well) or even heard about it. I can tell you that in 25 years I’ve never heard a word. When you find out that the government is effectively eradicating any evidence that your base and squadron ever existed, and the most polite thing any civilian’s ever said  was “What a shame, all for nothing”, then after so many years go by you begin to believe it. I know in my head that I made a difference, but the only people I care about, the only ones I’d ever trust, the ones who WERE THERE, have never muttered a syllable. My brain tells me that it didn’t really need to be said, yet my heart knows it made all the difference in the world. And for that I’ll forever be grateful. It’s amazing what a few kind words can do, particularly to someone who hasn’t heard any in years - at least not from those who count.<br><br>
I’ll be sending individual replies out as I can to each person who responded. I only wish I’d been involved in this site a long time ago.<br><br>
Not to change the subject, but I had encountered something before I posted my first letter that only contributed to my anger and helped me  almost go over the edge (if this is old news, sorry). Please check out the web site at:<br>
 http://jefferson.village.Virginia.EDU/sixties/HTML_docs/Texts/Humor/Weptronics/wep_entry.html<br><br>
A real piece of work, no? The illustration on the left side of each introductory page - and the message being given - reminds me of a lady named Cynthia Fuchs, vice-president the VNG, described at their web site: “Began working with Viet Nam Generation, Inc. in 1990. Director of the Film Studies Program and Associate Professor of English at George Mason University, Fairfax, VA”<br><br>
Her last name seems oddly appropriate as with one letter change you’d have the subject she seems to have a fascination with. That and certain aspects of the male anatomy which she somehow manipulates into being the subject of most of her writing I’ve been (un)privileged to read. She somehow relates both the act and male genitals to every problem society has ever had. See one of her less offensive efforts at:<br>
  <br>
http://jefferson.village.virginia.edu/sixties/HTML_docs/Texts/Reviews/Fuchs_Buddy_Counts.html<br><br>
She seems the likely inspiration for the “Weptronics” logo (I’m not sure if she hates all men or just wishes she had a “pair”, but the question is irrelevant). Now, despite the attacks on vets at this site I have nothing personal against her or the venomous Kali Tal (described in thread #6 Vietnam protest, and perhaps in others I have not read) whom I’ve had the misfortune of communicating with briefly (I trashed her e-mail to me after reading the first few words - I’d already heard it all for years). I respect their freedom of speech, no matter how sick or misguided. However, having this this site listed as a “catalog” web page for vets is a bit much. I found her in the Vietnam Veterans Home Page (at http://www.vietvet.org/) but it seems unlikely the people running it would knowingly have provided her a link (in The Post Exchange, News Stand, “The Village Elder” Magazine). I know nothing about the latter. Can anyone enlighten me as to the reason for these web pages and their crude attempt at humor?<br><br>
Having fought for freedom of speech I would not think of depriving these ladies of their fun, but I did e-mail  the president of the University of Virginia, John T. Casteen, III (jtc@Virginia.EDU or jtc@holmes.acc.virginia.edu), of of their sponsors, to request an honest explanation of what educational benefits the web pages might offer and how anyone might benefit from them. I doubt if I’ll receive a reply. My only guess is to piss off vets who will send angry mail to provide Cynthia Fuchs something else to write about (“penis envy”?). I sincerely wish these gals (a sexist nomenclature, no doubt) would find something more constructive to do than hassling vets and rewriting history ala Viet Nam Generation style to hand out as so-called text books. It’s people like this who led me to have little contact with society as extremists of all sorts will always be around at the detriment of the world as a hole. It was these extremists who helped drag out the war so long, and extremists on the other side who put us there in the first place. The rest of us end up as pawns amid their schemes, and the outcome is usually tragic regardless of their intentions. I truly wish they’d go away and leave the rest of us in piece, which is what they claim to represent in the first place.<br><br>
Sorry this is so long (again). Good luck to all...
<p><code>-- ganchors@bledsoe.net  (Bill “Tankerbird” Anchors) </code><p>


